        <li>/</li>
        <li class="text-[var(--color-foreground)]">JSON vs YAML</li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
      <h1>JSON vs YAML: Which Data Format Should You Use?</h1>

      <p>JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) and YAML (YAML Ain't Markup Language) are two of the most popular data serialization formats in software development. Both represent structured data as human-readable text, but they take fundamentally different approaches to syntax, readability, and flexibility. This guide compares them across every dimension that matters for your project.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a href="/tools/json-to-yaml" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-[var(--color-primary)] px-4 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:opacity-90">Try JSON to YAML Converter →</a>
        <a href="/tools/json-formatter" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--color-foreground)] transition-colors hover:bg-[var(--color-secondary)]">Try JSON Formatter →</a>
      </div>

      <h2>Quick Comparison Table</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full border-collapse rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border)] text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-[var(--color-secondary)]">
              <th class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">Feature</th>
              <th class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">JSON</th>
              <th class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">YAML</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Syntax Style</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Braces and brackets</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Indentation-based</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-[var(--color-secondary)]/50"><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Comments</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Not supported</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Supported (#)</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Multi-line Strings</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Escape sequences (\n)</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Block scalars (| and >)</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-[var(--color-secondary)]/50"><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Data Types</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">String, Number, Boolean, Null, Array, Object</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">All JSON types + Date, Binary, custom tags</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Anchors & Aliases</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Not supported</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Supported (&anchor / *alias)</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-[var(--color-secondary)]/50"><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Parsing Speed</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Very fast (native in JS)</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Slower (requires library)</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">File Size</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Larger (braces, quotes)</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">Smaller (no delimiters)</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-[var(--color-secondary)]/50"><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Superset Relationship</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">—</td><td class="border border-[var(--color-border)] px-4 py-2.5">YAML is a superset of JSON</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>JSON: The Universal Data Exchange Format</h2>

      <p>JSON emerged from JavaScript but has become the lingua franca of data exchange on the web. Its strict, unambiguous syntax makes it ideal for machine-to-machine communication. Every major programming language has built-in or standard-library JSON parsing. JavaScript engines can parse JSON natively via <code>JSON.parse()</code>, making it the fastest option for web applications.</p>

      <p>JSON's simplicity is its greatest strength — and its limitation. The format supports exactly six data types (string, number, boolean, null, array, object), has no comment syntax, and requires all strings to be double-quoted. This rigidity eliminates ambiguity but makes JSON verbose and less friendly for human-edited configuration.</p>

      <h2>YAML: The Human-Friendly Configuration Format</h2>

      <p>YAML was designed to be human-readable first. It uses indentation instead of braces, supports comments (essential for configuration files), offers multi-line strings with block scalars, and provides anchors and aliases for reusing values. YAML is a superset of JSON — every valid JSON document is also valid YAML.</p>

      <p>YAML dominates the DevOps and cloud-native ecosystem: Docker Compose, Kubernetes manifests, GitHub Actions, Ansible playbooks, and Helm charts all use YAML. Its readability makes it excellent for files that humans edit frequently.</p>

      <h2>When to Use JSON</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>API responses and requests</strong> — standard for REST and GraphQL</li>
        <li><strong>Data storage</strong> — MongoDB, CouchDB, and other document databases</li>
        <li><strong>Package manifests</strong> — package.json, tsconfig.json, composer.json</li>
        <li><strong>Browser/JavaScript applications</strong> — native parsing, no library needed</li>
        <li><strong>Inter-service communication</strong> — unambiguous, fast to parse</li>
        <li><strong>When you need strict typing</strong> — no implicit type coercion</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>When to Use YAML</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Configuration files</strong> — Docker Compose, Kubernetes, CI/CD pipelines</li>
        <li><strong>Infrastructure as Code</strong> — Ansible, CloudFormation, Helm</li>
        <li><strong>Files edited by humans</strong> — comments + readability matter</li>
        <li><strong>Complex nested structures</strong> — indentation is more scannable than braces</li>
        <li><strong>Multi-line content</strong> — block scalars for templates, scripts, descriptions</li>
        <li><strong>When DRY matters</strong> — anchors and aliases reduce repetition</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Common Pitfalls</h2>

      <h3>YAML's "Norway Problem"</h3>
      <p>YAML 1.1 (still used by many parsers) treats bare <code>NO</code>, <code>no</code>, <code>off</code>, and <code>false</code> as boolean false. This infamously caused problems for country code "NO" (Norway) being parsed as <code>false</code>. YAML 1.2 fixed this, but not all parsers have updated. Always quote strings that could be misinterpreted.</p>

      <h3>Indentation Sensitivity</h3>
      <p>YAML's indentation rules are strict — tabs are not allowed (only spaces), and inconsistent indentation causes silent data structure changes rather than parse errors. This makes YAML more error-prone in collaborative editing than JSON.</p>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>

      <h3>Is YAML really a superset of JSON?</h3>
      <p>Yes, since YAML 1.2. Any valid JSON document can be parsed by a YAML 1.2 compliant parser. This means you can gradually migrate from JSON to YAML by adding YAML features (comments, anchors) incrementally.</p>

      <h3>Which is better for APIs?</h3>
      <p>JSON. It's the universal standard for web APIs, has native browser support, is faster to parse, and its strict syntax prevents ambiguity. YAML is better suited for configuration files that humans edit directly.</p>

      <h3>Can I convert between JSON and YAML without data loss?</h3>
      <p>JSON to YAML is always lossless (since YAML is a superset). YAML to JSON may lose comments, anchors/aliases, and custom tags, but the actual data values are preserved.</p>

